com.snapbundle.model.context

Interface IObjectInteraction

  • All Superinterfaces:
    IAccountContext, IAccountDomainResource<IObjectInteraction>, IDomainResource<IObjectInteraction>, IMoniker, IReferentialObject, ITypedObject, IUrnNamespace
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    ObjectInteraction

    public interface IObjectInteraction
extends IAccountDomainResource<IObjectInteraction>, IReferentialObject, ITypedObject
    Captures an explicit interaction between two existing IObject instances that already exist in the system.

    The getObject() is generally treated as the recipient of the interaction, while the IReferentialObject is considered the initiator. As a concrete example, the person 'Jason' would be identified as the IReferentialObject while the getObject() would be the vehicle 'Jeep' with the ITypedObject.getType() of Drives to successfully capture the simple interaction that "Jason drives the Jeep."

    Additional metadata, including IFile, IGeospatialEntry, IMetadata, and ITagAssignment are typically used to capture additional context about the interaction. Returning to the driving example, the files might captures photos taken of Jason behind the driver's wheel, a geospatial record to capture the route that Jason drove, metadata to capture the mileage of the vehicle at the start of the trip and at the end of the trip, and tags to represent landmarks along the path that the vehicle drove.

    Interactions capture a recurring pattern of interactivity between two objects. In other words, interactions are used to capture 0, 1, or many relationships between objects.

    If you are looking for a binary or true-false existence check, the recommended construct is to use an IRelationship instead of an interaction.
